04831nam a22007455i 9780674369788DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20142014mau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)900717618  a97806743697887 a10.4159/harvard.97806743697882doi  a(DE-B1597)427915  a(OCoLC)881627434  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aBJ161b.I59 2014eb 7aPHI0050002bisacsh04a170.9382231 aInwood, Brad, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEthics After Aristotle /cBrad Inwood. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (176 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCarl Newell Jackson Lectures ;v1200tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. Working in the Wake of Genius -- t2. Flirting with Hedonism (It’s Only Natural) -- t3. The Turning Point: From Critolaus to Cicero -- t4. Bridging the Gap: Aristotelian Ethics in the Early Roman Empire -- t5. Alexander and Imperial Aristotelianism -- tNotes -- tNote on the Ancient Texts -- tBibliography -- tSource Index -- tSubject Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom the earliest times, philosophers and others have thought deeply about ethical questions. But it was Aristotle who founded ethics as a discipline with clear principles and well-defined boundaries. Ethics After Aristotle focuses on the reception of Aristotelian ethical thought in the Hellenistic and Roman worlds, underscoring the thinker's enduring influence on the philosophers who followed in his footsteps from 300 BCE to 200 CE. Beginning with Aristotle's student and collaborator Theophrastus, Brad Inwood traces the development of Aristotelian ethics up to the third-century Athenian philosopher Alexander of Aphrodisias. He shows that there was no monolithic tradition in the school, but a rich variety of moral theory. The philosophers of the Peripatetic school produced surprisingly varied theories in dialogue with other philosophical traditions, generating rich insight into human virtue and happiness. What unifies the different strands of thought--what makes them distinctively Aristotelian--is a form of ethical naturalism: that our knowledge of the good and virtuous life depends first on understanding our place in the natural world, and second on the exercise of our natural dispositions in distinctively human activities. What is now referred to as "virtue ethics," Inwood argues, is a less important part of Aristotle's legacy than the naturalistic approach Aristotle articulated and his philosophical descendants developed further. Offering a wide range of ways of thinking about ethics from an ancient perspective, Ethics After Aristotle is a penetrating study of how philosophy evolves in the wake of an unusually powerful and original thinker.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEthics, Ancient. 0aInfluence (Literary, artistic, etc.). 0aPhilosophie. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Complete Package 2014z9783110369526oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2014z9783110370393oZDB-23-DPH08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066590140uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067436978840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674369788423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674369788.jpg  a978-3-11-066590-1  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-